The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Tata Steel profit rises 50%
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Tata Steel profit rises 50%
          OUR BUREAU                          Koushik Chatterjee (right),vice-president (finance) of Tata Steel, in Mumbai on Friday. (Fotocorp)                                  
	Oct. 24: The net profit of Tata Steel for the second quarter ended September 30 has surged 50.13 per cent to Rs 1,787.81 crore from 1,190.83 crore in the same period last year.        
	Total income rose 43.14 per cent to Rs 6,850.67 crore for the quarter under review from Rs 4,785.90 crore in the corresponding period last fiscal.        
	For the six months ended September 30, the worlds sixth largest steel maker reported a net profit of Rs 3,276.21 crore, up 36 per cent over the year-ago period. Total income during the first half of the current fiscal rose to Rs 13,016.36 crore from Rs 9,009.36 crore in the year-ago period.        
	However, the Tata Steel scrip today touched a 52-week low of Rs 174.15 on the Bombay Stock Exchange in a weak domestic market. It closed at Rs 178.30, down 14.46 per cent.        
	Lever profit        
	Hindustan Unilever (HUL) has reported a 33.95 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 546.61 crore for the third quarter ended September 30.         
	Its total income during the quarter was Rs 4,110.91 crore, an increase of 21.08 per cent from Rs 3,395.17 crore in the same period a year ago.        
	According to vice-chairman D. Sundaram, the FMCG major witnessed broad-based growth in terms of value and volume during the reporting quarter. The prices of raw materials, especially crude-based inputs, impacted the company during the quarter, he said.        
	The volatility of commodity prices also had an impact on the prices of raw materials, Sundaram said. We are seeing a softening of commodity prices. If it continues, it would be good for market development and business expansion, he said.        
	On pricing, Sundaram said the companys approach had been consistent.        
	ITC show        
	Diversified conglomerate ITC Ltd has registered 4.13 per cent growth in net profit for the second quarter ended September 30 at Rs 802.72 crore against Rs 770.87 crore in the same quarter a year ago.        
	Net income of the company rose to Rs 3,862.67 crore for the quarter under review from Rs 3,318.36 crore in the same period a year ago.        
	For the half-year ended September 30, the company posted a net profit of Rs 1,551.39 crore against Rs 1,553.74 crore in the corresponding period a year ago. Net income rose to Rs 7,796.67 crore in the first half of the current fiscal from Rs 6,633.05 crore in the same quarter last fiscal.        
	During the quarter, the company made a further investment of Rs 60 crore in the equity capital of ITC Infotech India, a wholly-owned subsidiary of the company.                                                                                                                                     
